{"parse":{"title":"College of Sociology","pageid":794900,"revid":826340430,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content ambox-Refimprove\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Question_book-new.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png\" width=\"50\" height=\"39\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/75px-Question_book-new.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/100px-Question_book-new.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"512\" data-file-height=\"399\" /></a></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>needs additional citations for <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability\" title=\"Wikipedia:Verifiability\">verification</a></b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please help <a class=\"external text\" href=\"//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=College_of_Sociology&amp;action=edit\">improve this article</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing_with_Wiki_Markup/1\" title=\"Help:Introduction to referencing with Wiki Markup/1\">adding citations to reliable sources</a>. Unsourced material may be challenged and removed.</span>  <small><i>(September 2013)</i></small><small class=\"hide-when-compact\"><i> (<a href=\"/wiki/Help:Maintenance_template_removal\" title=\"Help:Maintenance template removal\">Learn how and when to remove this template message</a>)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The <b>College of Sociology</b> (<i>Coll\u00e8ge de Sociologie</i> in French) was a loosely-knit group of French <a href=\"/wiki/Intellectual\" title=\"Intellectual\">intellectuals</a>, named after the informal discussion series that they held in Paris between 1937 and 1939, when it was disrupted by the war. \n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=College_of_Sociology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Founding members include some of France's most well-known intellectuals of the interwar period, including <a href=\"/wiki/Georges_Bataille\" title=\"Georges Bataille\">Georges Bataille</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Roger_Caillois\" title=\"Roger Caillois\">Roger Caillois</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Pierre_Klossowski\" title=\"Pierre Klossowski\">Pierre Klossowski</a>, Jules Monnerot, Pierre Libra and Georges Ambrosino. Participants also included <a href=\"/wiki/Hans_Mayer\" title=\"Hans Mayer\">Hans Mayer</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Jean_Paulhan\" title=\"Jean Paulhan\">Jean Paulhan</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Jean_Wahl\" title=\"Jean Wahl\">Jean Wahl</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Michel_Leiris\" title=\"Michel Leiris\">Michel Leiris</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Alexandre_Koj%C3%A8ve\" title=\"Alexandre Koj\u00e8ve\">Alexandre Koj\u00e8ve</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Andr%C3%A9_Masson\" title=\"Andr\u00e9 Masson\">Andr\u00e9 Masson</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/Walter_Benjamin\" title=\"Walter Benjamin\">Walter Benjamin</a> was invited to give lectures, but these never materialized.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The members of the College were united in their dissatisfaction with <a href=\"/wiki/Surrealism\" title=\"Surrealism\">surrealism</a>. They believed that surrealism's focus on the unconscious privileged the individual over society, and obscured the social dimension of human experience. \n</p><p>In contrast to this, the members of the College focused on \"Sacred Sociology, implying the study of all manifestations of social existence where the active presence of the sacred is clear.\" The group drew on work in <a href=\"/wiki/Anthropology\" title=\"Anthropology\">anthropology</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Sociology\" title=\"Sociology\">sociology</a> which focused on the way that human communities engaged in collective rituals or acts of distribution such as <a href=\"/wiki/Potlatch\" title=\"Potlatch\">potlatch</a>. It was here, in moments of intense communal experience, rather than the individualistic dreams and reveries of surrealism, that the College of Sociology sought the essence of humanity. \n</p><p>The group met for two years and lectured on many topics, including the structure of the <a href=\"/wiki/Army\" title=\"Army\">army</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Marquis_de_Sade\" title=\"Marquis de Sade\">Marquis de Sade</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/English_monarchy\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"English monarchy\">English monarchy</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Literature\" title=\"Literature\">literature</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Human_sexuality\" title=\"Human sexuality\">sexuality</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Hitler\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hitler\">Hitler</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Hegel\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Hegel\">Hegel</a>. This focus, and in particular their interest in indigenous cultures, was part of a wider trend towards <a href=\"/wiki/Primitivism\" title=\"Primitivism\">primitivism</a> of the time.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=College_of_Sociology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Refugees in France by this time.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Esther Leslie, Walter Benjmain (London, UK; Reaktion Books, 2007).</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Sources\">Sources</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=College_of_Sociology&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Sources\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Hollier, Denis. <i>Le Coll\u00e8ge de Sociologie, 1937-1939</i>. Paris: Gallimard. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/2-07-032763-9\" title=\"Special:BookSources/2-07-032763-9\">2-07-032763-9</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Le+Coll%C3%A8ge+de+Sociologie%2C+1937-1939&amp;rft.place=Paris&amp;rft.pub=Gallimard&amp;rft.isbn=2-07-032763-9&amp;rft.aulast=Hollier&amp;rft.aufirst=Denis&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACollege+of+Sociology\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> (A collection of texts from Caillois, Leiris, Bataille, and others which were presented at the <i>Coll\u00e8ge</i>, with a well documented introduction.)</li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Moebius, Stephan. <i>Die Zauberlehrlinge: Soziologiegeschichte des Coll\u00e8ge de Sociologie</i>. Konstanz: UVK. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/3-89669-532-0\" title=\"Special:BookSources/3-89669-532-0\">3-89669-532-0</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Die+Zauberlehrlinge%3A+Soziologiegeschichte+des+Coll%C3%A8ge+de+Sociologie&amp;rft.place=Konstanz&amp;rft.pub=UVK&amp;rft.isbn=3-89669-532-0&amp;rft.aulast=Moebius&amp;rft.aufirst=Stephan&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACollege+of+Sociology\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span> (About the <i>Coll\u00e8ge</i>, its members (Bataille, Leiris, and Walter Benjamin), sociological impact (Marcel Mauss, Robert Hertz, Emile Durkheim) and its influence on other philosophers (Derrida, Foucault, Baudrillard, etc.)</li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Richman, Mich\u00e8le H. <i>Sacred Revolutions: Durkheim and the College De Sociologie</i>. Minneapolis: University of Minnesota Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-8166-3974-4\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-8166-3974-4\">0-8166-3974-4</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Sacred+Revolutions%3A+Durkheim+and+the+College+De+Sociologie&amp;rft.place=Minneapolis&amp;rft.pub=University+of+Minnesota+Press&amp;rft.isbn=0-8166-3974-4&amp;rft.aulast=Richman&amp;rft.aufirst=Mich%C3%A8le+H.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ACollege+of+Sociology\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1272\nCached time: 20180908154906\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.088 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.134 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 241/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 8072/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 98/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 1/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 605/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.048/10.0